	<div class="the-comment" id="comment-1465115">

		<div class="comment-meta">

			<span class="comment-author">Ricky Jay</span>
			<span class="comment-link">
				<a href="#comment-1465115" title="Comment Permalink">
					<span class="comment-date">January 20, 2014</span>
					<span class="comment-middot">&middot;</span>
					<span class="comment-time">10:17 am</span>
				</a>
			</span>
		</div>
		<div class="comment-content" style="display:block;">

			<p>Risks of chemical and petroleum product leaks from storage tanks and associated piping, according to what I understand, is virtually unregulated at the federal level and not regulated by many states. This is very different from tanks and piping which hold &#8220;hazardous wastes&#8221;, that have stringent federal standards. For all such tanks and piping, adequate inspection by public authorities is another issue greatly weakened due to the financial condition at all government levels.</p>
<p>One approach to reducing risk can be to issue strong federal regulations which include the requirement of liability insurance whose fees would be scaled to the design, condition and location of each chemical and petroleum tank: if high risk exists, the owner would pay high insurance premiums; low risks &#8212; low premiums. </p>
<p>Reducing risks of chemical and petroleum product leaks comes at a price for regulation and insurance, but not reducing risks inevitably results in very expensive cleanup costs, health and environmental impacts. Some of these impacts are irreversible, long-term, and end in chronic illness and/or death. </p>
<p>Regulation by the States ( as opposed to the federal government ) is compromised by interstate competition that induces a race-to-the-bottom. In my opinion, the Nation needs comprehensive federal umbrella regulation, financial incentives for owners to invest and comply, and inspection standards and schedules implemented by the States.</p>
<p>Not investing on risk reduction will certainly invite more events like that in West Virginia along the &#8220;chemical valley&#8221; bordering the Elk River. What does the American public want and need?</p>
<p>Ps. Some poorly run companies that own tank systems may go out of business and some job losses may occur, but many jobs will be added because of the need for inspection and replacing higher risk tanks. Long term, reducing safety, health and environmental risk will benefit well-run companies and the public.</p>

