			<p><a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/01/15/testing-the-waters-investigating-questions-about-the-west-virginia-chemical-spill/?_php=true&#038;_type=blogs&#038;_php=true&#038;_type=blogs&#038;_r=1" rel="nofollow">//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/01/15/testing-the-waters-investigating-questions-about-the-west-virginia-chemical-spill/?_php=true&#038;_type=blogs&#038;_php=true&#038;_type=blogs&#038;_r=1</a></p>
<p>I am sure that this was very scary for West Virginia residents.  I canât imagine what they were going through.  I know that we need chemical plants and could not survive as a nation without them. The government needs to have stronger laws on regulating chemical plants.  It appears that they did attempt to help the locals by supplying bottled water but im sure it was not enough.  I canât imagine trying to drink the water after this I think I would always wonder if it was safe.  The local businesses in the area took major hits to their income.  Did the government help them? Iâm sure that it was not enough.  The wildlife that live and drink from this river were probably contaminated also.   I would be scared to eat any of those animals for years. </p>
<p>If the state were to regulate the water supply more frequently then they may have caught this problem earlier. If the chemical company would have checked their holding tanks more frequently this spill may not have happened.  The state would also need to test the wildlife in the area for years to come.  Iâm sure that the company has suffered a great deal from all of this too.  I am sure that they would never mean for this to happen and I bet that they have apologized to the town and community.  I am sure that they have enforced tougher rules and regulations in regards to their chemical storage.  I bet they will not let this happen again and if it did then I think the government needs to shut them down.</p>

		</div>
	</div><!-- #comment-## -->
</div> <!-- end comment text -->

